irculating T3 and DIO3 protects fetal development","DIO1 produces circulating T3 and DIO3 provides pituitary feedback"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe three deiodinase enzymes have distinct physiological roles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDIO1 produces circulating T3\u003C/strong\u003E through peripheral conversion of thyroxine (T4) to triiodothyronine (T3)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDIO2 provides pituitary feedback\u003C/strong\u003E through local conversion of T4 to T3 in the anterior pituitary, controlling thyroid-stimulating hormone secretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDIO3 protects fetal development\u003C/strong\u003E by inactivating excess thyroid hormones during crucial developmental periods\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options suggesting that \u003Cstrong\u003EDIO2 produces circulating T3\u003C/strong\u003E or that \u003Cstrong\u003EDIO3 provides pituitary feedback\u003C/strong\u003E do not accurately reflect the specialized functions of these enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Deiodinase type 1 (DIO1) produces most circulating triiodothyronine (T3)","Deiodinase type 2 (DIO2) provides local feedback to the anterior pituitary","Deiodinase type 3 (DIO3) is crucial for protecting the developing fetus from excess thyroid hormone"],"references":["Brent GA. Mechanisms of thyroid hormone action. J Clin Invest. 2012 Sep;122(9):3035-43. doi: 10.1172/JCI60047. Epub 2012 Sep 4. PMID: 22945636; PMCID: PMC3433956","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrin